# popbio
# December 4 2018
# CU

# uses matrix population models to estimate a pupulation's vital rates and build projection matrices.

#typically plants

# takes in a leslie, or transition matrix (A) and a population vector (n) 

#contains functions that give you predictions about how population is expected to change and what life stages have greates effect (senstitivities and elasticities) on population growth (lambda). 

library(popbio)
library(ggplot2)

stages <- c("seed", "rosette", "flower")
A <- matrix(c(
  0.5,    0,     50, 
  0.1,    0.2,   0, 
  0,      0.6,   0.9), nrow = 3, byrow = TRUE, dimnames = list(stages, stages))
A
##         seed rosette flower
## seed     0.5     0.0   50.0
## rosette  0.1     0.2    0.0
## flower   0.0     0.6    0.9
n <- c(0,0,10) #plant a garden of 10 flowering lavendar plants
n
## [1]  0  0 10
p <- pop.projection(A, n, iterations=10) 

# multiplies A and n matrices to get number of individulas at each stage after 1 year (t+1). Does this agian and again (iteratons) until stable stage distribution is met. 

p
## $lambda
## [1] 2.004351
## 
## $stable.stage
##       seed    rosette     flower 
## 0.92221816 0.05091139 0.02687045 
## 
## $stage.vectors

## flower  10   9   8.1  37.29   81.561  128.3049  260.9744   575.920

p$lambda #annual populaiton growth
## [1] 2.004351
#lambda<1 decline
#lambda>1 increase
#lambda=1 stable

p$stable.stage #stable stage distribution
##       seed    rosette     flower 
## 0.92221816 0.05091139 0.02687045
p$stage.vector #by year 9 you'll have 900 plants!! 
##          0   1     2      3        4         5         6         7
## seed     0 500 700.0 755.00 2242.000 5199.0500 9014.7700 17556.106
## rosette  0   0  50.0  80.00   91.500  242.5000  568.4050  1015.158

##                 8         9
## seed    37574.051 75158.164
## rosette  1958.642  4149.134
## flower   1127.423  2189.866
#plot stage distributions:
stage.vector.plot(p$stage.vectors, col=2:4) #havn't reaches stable state yet, need to increase iterations to 15

#my lavender garden is OUT OF CONTROL! 

#so, what life stage or transition (vital rate) should I target to get my garden under control?

# do a little research and find that seed germination is less successful in wet soils, so you plant your lavender in a wet part of the garden:
